Adds TorqueCcBuiltinTest.JsReturnAdaptorDispatch, the first cctest
case that binds Builtin::kTorqueCcTest_JsReturn as a JSFunction on
the global object and invokes it through V8's full
JS-call → AdaptorWithBuiltinExitFrame1 → CPP-linkage dispatch
pipeline.

To split the V8-internal binding code (heap/factory.h, api-inl.h)
from Node's node_test_fixture.h, the actual bind helper lives in
test_torque_cc_builtin_helpers.{h,cc}. The two headers each define
TRACE_EVENT0 and enum CategoryGroupEnabledFlags at global scope
(V8 via src/tracing/trace-event.h transitively included by
heap/factory.h → heap.h → gc-tracer.h; Node via src/tracing/
trace_event_common.h included by node_internals.h) and cannot
coexist in a single TU. Keeping the bridge in its own .cc whose
include set excludes node_test_fixture.h sidesteps the collision
without touching upstream V8 or Node.

While writing this test the first green run exposed an emission
bug in Task 5.3's JS-linkage CPP-ABI path: explicit JS args were
unpacked as Cast<Inner>(args[explicit_index]) with explicit_index
starting at 0. V8's BuiltinArguments::operator[] treats index 0
as the RECEIVER (kReceiverIndex = kArgsIndex, see
src/builtins/builtins-utils.h:30,64) — args[1] is the first real
arg, matching the BUILTIN(Name) convention's args.at<T>(1).
Previously every whitelisted JS-linkage builtin would silently
read its first parameter as the receiver; with this fix,
`TorqueCcTest_JsReturn.call(undefined, 'test-marker')` correctly
returns 'test-marker' instead of `undefined`. Change is a one-
character edit (explicit_index → explicit_index + 1), with the
surrounding comment rewritten to match actual BuiltinArguments
indexing.

cctest run (all four cases PASS):
  DirectInvocation, DispatchTableLookup, Phase5ScriptRunSmoke,
  JsReturnAdaptorDispatch.
d8 smoke (print(1+2), print("hello")) and the harness (14
torque fixtures OK) both unaffected — harness still uses
out/Release.baseline/torque (pre-fix) as planned.

Part of Phase 5 (revised) Task 5.6.
