From 489d76aa53824a6fdeddd9fc34923448cef6eb8d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Brandon Payton <brandon@happycode.net>
Date: Thu, 23 Apr 2026 17:57:28 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 59/94] torque: kCCBuiltins preamble gains forward-decls +
 True_0/False_0 shims
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Two kCCBuiltins -tq-ccbuiltins.cc layout fixes for Task 5.8, combined
in one commit because both are preamble-level changes to the file
composition in GenerateImplementation's WriteFile call:

1. Forward declarations for TqRuntime<name>_<N> macros
   (Task 5.8 defect 1)

   The kCCBuiltins fourth pass emits builtin bodies into
   cc_builtins_ccfile; the fifth pass appends macro bodies to the
   same stream. Call order in the stream is thus: [builtin body,
   macro bodies]. The builtin body references macros (e.g.
   `TqRuntimeCast_JSArray_1`) before their inline definitions — a
   use-before-decl compile error in C++.

   Visit(TorqueMacro*)'s f.PrintDeclaration writes a forward decl of
   each macro to csa_headerfile(), which for kCCBuiltins resolves to
   streams.cc_builtins_headerfile. That stream was accumulated but
   never emitted anywhere. Fix: prepend the header stream's contents
   to the body stream when composing the -tq-ccbuiltins.cc output,
   so forward declarations appear before the builtin body.

2. NamespaceConstant shims for True_0 / False_0
   (Task 5.8 defect 4)

   The kCCBuiltins pass only visits Builtin declarables (skip-filter
   at VisitAllDeclarables:3972). NamespaceConstant visitors are
   gated off because Visit(NamespaceConstant) uses CSAGenerator/
   state_-dependent machinery and would SIGSEGV under kCCBuiltins.
   Result: accessor functions like `True_0(isolate)` /
   `False_0(isolate)` — which ArrayIsArray's Torque body calls — are
   never defined for the CC side. Compile fails with
   `use of undeclared identifier 'True_0'; did you mean 'True'?`.

   Proper fix (NamespaceConstant CC emission with full torque body
   lowering) is Phase 6 scope. For Task 5.8 we ship pragmatic inline
   accessors in every -tq-ccbuiltins.cc preamble:

     inline Tagged<True> True_0(Isolate*) {
       return Cast<True>(ReadOnlyRoots(isolate).true_value());
     }
     inline Tagged<False> False_0(Isolate*) {
       return Cast<False>(ReadOnlyRoots(isolate).false_value());
     }

   Both are `inline`, so cross-TU duplicates are ODR-legal. The
   torque-suffix `_0` on the names tracks base.tq's fresh-id counter
   state at the point these consts are declared; if future torque
   source edits reorder declarations and shift the suffix, this
   commit's hardcoded names will need updating (documented inline).

   Also adds `src/roots/roots-inl.h` to the preamble's #include set
   (needed for ReadOnlyRoots).

Together, these let array-isarray-tq-ccbuiltins.cc compile and link;
d8 now runs `print(Array.isArray([1,2,3]))` → `true` end-to-end.

Closes Task 5.8 defects (1) and (4).
