Subject: [PATCH 93/94] torque: Builtin_Add and Builtin_Subtract delegate to V8
 NumberValue + NewNumber
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Phase 9.7 refactor: replace Phase 8/8.1's hand-written native int64
Smi arithmetic with V8-API delegation. Each bridge shrinks from
~30 LoC of arithmetic + Smi/HeapNumber dispatch to ~5 LoC of
`Object::NumberValue + factory->NewNumber(double)` — the same
fast path Object::Add takes internally for Number+Number.

Why not Object::Add directly? It returns MaybeDirectHandle<Object>
(handles string concat / ToPrimitive failure) — for our statically-
typed Number+Number case the failure branch is unreachable, and
the MaybeHandle ceremony is more code than the direct delegation.

Why these two but not Builtin_NonNumberToNumeric? That one already
delegates to Object::ToNumeric (Phase 8 got it right); no rewrite
needed.

Behavior is byte-identical for Number+Number — factory->NewNumber's
internal Smi/HeapNumber discrimination matches our prior int64-
overflow-checked dispatch on every input. Verified by 16/16 cctest
+ 26/26 d8-smoke (including ++MAX_SAFE_INTEGER overflow,
--(-MAX_SAFE_INTEGER) underflow, 1.5/0.5 HeapNumber paths, BigInt
arms via TFC dispatch). Excluding-anchor 8169724e unchanged.

Sets the pattern for Phase 10+ TFC bridges: each new bridge is a
~5 LoC delegation to the appropriate V8 high-level API rather than
re-implementing builtin semantics in C++.
